<div id="content">
<h1>Introduction to Algebra</h1>

<p>Out of all 4 categories of competition math, middle schoolers likely have the most experience with algebra. Algebra is a branch of mathematics that uses symbols such as <em>x</em> or <em>y</em> to represent unknown variables or changing systems. While relatively simple, it lays the foundation for tons of higher-level fields such as calculus, cryptography, topology, etc. Algebra in a sense may be considered the most fundamental of our 4 categories, as most problems in the other 3 books will likely use some facet of algebra to a certain extent.</p>

<h2 id="linear-equations">Linear Equations</h2>
<h2 id="what-is-a-linear-equation-one-variable-linear-equations">What is a Linear Equation + One Variable Linear Equations</h2>
<p>Sometimes, we want to find the value of something, so we produce equations with variables to represent–and ultimately determine–a numerical value. For example, if we say Max the fruit merchant has three apples that are worth $\$6$ altogether, and we want to find the value of just one apple, we can represent it as $3x = 6$. We've chosen a variable, $x$, to represent the value of what we're trying to find: the price of a pair of glasses. To solve for $x$, we may divide both sides by $3$ to reach the equation $x = 2$. Thus, we have deduced that one apple costs $\boxed{\$2}$.</p>

<div class="exercise-section">
<h4>Exercises</h4>

<p>For all of the following equations, solve for $x$.</p>

<ol>
<li>5x = 120</li>
<li>2x+7 = 4x+5</li>
<li>3x+18 = 9x+6</li>
<li>17x+3 = 34x + 6</li>
<li>4x+2 = 4x+3</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="solution-section">
<h4>Solutions</h4>
<ol>
<li>Divide both sides of the equation by $5$ to get $\boxed{24}$</li>
<li>Subtract $2x$ from both sides to isolate $x$ on one side of the equation. Now, we're left with $7 = 2x + 5$. Now, subtract $5$ from both sides to get $2 = 2x$. Finally, divide both sides by $2$ to get $x = \boxed{1}$.</li>
<li>Subtract $3x$ and $6$ from both sides to get $6x = 12$. Thus, $x = \boxed{2}$.</li>
<li>Notice that the left side of the equation is a multiple of the right side of the equation. This means that there are $\boxed{\infty}$ solutions.</li>
<li>Subtracting $4x$ from both sides, we get that $2=3$ which is obviously not true. Thus, there are $\boxed{0}$ solutions.</li>
</ol>
</div>
<h2 id="graphing-2-variable-equations">Graphing + 2 variable equations.</h2>
<p>Oftentimes, we represent simple relationships with graphs or two variable equations. For example, if we look at Max's apples again, we may represent the total cost of apples bought as $y = 2x$. It is important to note that the $x$ here is different from the $x$ from our previous problem. Here, $y$ represents the total cost of apples and $x$ represents the number of apples being purchased. Depending on the value of $x$ (how many apples you buy), the value of $y$ (the total cost) changes. As you may have guessed, linear equations are called linear because when you graph them, they form straight lines. Here is the graph representation of our problem:</p>



<p>Here, we have an $x$ axis (the horizontal black line) and a $y$ axis (the vertical black line). If we follow the red line, which is our relationship $y = 2x$, when we change the value of $x$, the value of $y$ also changes. When $x = 1$, $y=2$, and when $x=2$, $y=4$. This red line is thus a graphical representation of our relationship. We denote any point on this graph as an ordered pair like $(1, 2)$. Here, the $1$ represents the $x$ value and the $2$ represents the $y$ value. We call the number next to the $x$ the coefficient, and it denotes how many multiples of $x$ there are. When the coefficient of $y$ is $1$, the coefficient of $x$ may also be known as the slope of the line. The slope denotes how much $y$ changes when $x$ changes. Here, when $x$ changes by $1$, $y$ changes by $2$.</p>

<div class="exercise-section">
<h4>Exercises</h4>

<ol>
<li>Graph the following equation on a piece of paper: $y = 2x + 1$</li>
<li>Find the slope of the line represented by this equation: $2x + y = 4x + 3$</li>
<li>Which equation has the greater slope: 
<br>$4y = 8x + 28$
<br>$y = 3x - 4$</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="solution-section">
<h4>Solutions</h4>
<ol>
<li>Consult desmos</li>
<li>Substract $2x$ from both sides to get $y = 2x + 3$. The coefficient of $y$ here is $1$, so the slope of this line is $\boxed{2}$.</li>
<li>Notice that the slope of equation $b$ is $3$ because the $y$ coefficient is already $1$. Now, let's try to reduce the coefficient of $y$ to $1$ for equation $a$ by dividing both sides by $4$. After doing so, we reach $y = 2x + 7$. Thus, the slope here is $2$. This means that equation $\boxed{b}$ has the greater slope.</li>
</ol>
</div>

<h2 id="multivariable-systems">Multivariable Systems</h2>

<h2 id="what-is-a-system">What is a System/Intro to 2-Variable Systems</h2>

<p>Sometimes, you'll be given a problem where you actually have $2$ unknown variables. Generally, you may call these variables $x$ and $y$ respectively, although you can really use any sort of symbol to represent them. If you have $2$ or more equations denoting the relationship between these $2$ variables, you will be able to deduce the value of these variables (or reach the conclusion that there are no such values that exist). For example, if we look at the equation $y = 4x +3$, there are infinite such pairs of values that satisfy the relationship. $y=7, x=1$ works, but so does $y=11, x=2$. Another way to think about this is that if we graph this, we get a line. Any point on this line satisfies the conditions, so there are infinite solutions. However, if we have a system such as,</p>
$\begin{align}
y &= 4x + 3\\
y &= 2x + 5
\end{align}$

<p>we can see $2$ lines. There is only $1$ point where these $2$ lines overlap, and so that point is the point that satisfies both conditions.</p>

<h2 id="substitution">Substitution</h2>

<p>A popular technique when it comes to solving linear systems is known as substitution. If we look at our example above, we may see that $y$ is equal to $4x + 3$, but it is also equal to $2x + 5$. This means that $4x + 3$ is also equal to $2x + 5$. We have now effectively turned this into a $1$ variable equation that we can now solve. Whenever we're dealing with a system with multiple variables, we always want to simplify it down to a $1$ variable equation. This goes for both substitution (which we're now covering) and elimination (which we will cover after this).</p>

<div class="exercise-section">
<h4>Exercises - For all of the following, find values for $x$ and $y$ that satisfy both conditions.
</h4>
<ol>
<li>$x + 3y = 4, 5y - 2x = -30$</li>
<li>$2y = 3x - 7, y = 5x - 14$</li>
<li>$x = 2y + 4, 2x = 4y + 9$</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="solution-section">
<h4>Solutions</h4>
<ol>
<li>For our first equation, subtracts $3y$ from both sides to get $x = -3y + 4$. Now, substitute this into the second equation to get $5y - 2(-3y+4) = -30$. If we expand this equation, we get $5y + 6y - 8 = -30$, meaning $11y =  -22$. Thus, $y = -2$. Now, we simply plug this value of $y$ back into any of the equations. Let's choose the first equation. If we plug in $y= -2$, we get $x - 6 = 4$. This means that $x = 10$. Thus, our answer is $x = 10, y = -2$. In other words, $\boxed{10, -2}$.</li>
<li>Going faster now, we already have $y$ by itself on equation $2$, so substitute that into equation $1$ to get $10x - 28 = 3x - 7$. Now, solve normally to get $7x = 21$ meaning $x = 3$. Plugging this into the second equation, we get $y = 1$. Thus, our answer is $\boxed{(3, 1)}$.</li>
<li>If we substitute the first equation to the second, we get that $4y + 8 = 4y + 9$. This means that $8 = 9$. Obviously, this is not true, so we reach the conclusion that there are $\boxed{no solutions}$. Sometimes, systems have no solutions at all.</li>
</ol></div>

<h2 id="elimination">Elimination</h2>

<p>The other predominant technique for solving systems is known as elimination. This involves turning the system into a $1$ variable equation by cancelling out one of the variables. For example, let's look at our previous system.</p>

<p>$y = 4x + 3 $</p>
<p>$y = 2x + 5$</p>

<p>To use elimination, let's subtract the bottom equation from the top equation. To do this, we subtract the left side of the bottom equation from the left side of the top equation and the right side of the bottom equation from the right side of the top equation. Essentially, the sides just match up. Now, we have $0 = 2x - 2$. Now, this is just a $1$ variable equation that we can solve. The trick we just did is that because both $y$ coefficients were the same, we can just subtract one from the other to effectively remove $y$ from the systems altogether.</p>

<div class="exercise-section">
<h4>Exercises</h4>
<ol>
<li>$y = 2x + 4, 2y = 5x + 20$</li>
<li>$2x + 3y = -11, 4x - 3y = 23$</li>
<li>$y = 2x + 9, 3y - 27 = 6x$</li>
</ol>
</div>
<div class="solution-section">
<h4>Solutions</h4>
<ol>
<li>Multiply both sides of equation $1$ by $2$ to get $2y = 4x + 8$. Now, subtract this from equation $2$ to get $0 = x + 12$. This means that $x = -12$, and $y = -20$. In other words, the solution is $<span class="boxed">$(-12, -20)$</span></li>
<li>If we add both of these equation together, we get $6x = 12$. Notice that the $y$s cancelled out. Now, we get $x = 2$ and $y = -5$. Thus, $\boxed{(2, -5)}$. Elimination doesn't always have to come in the form of subtraction. We can use addition as well.</li>
<li>Multiplying both sides of equation $1$ by $3$ and subtracting the result from equation $2$, we get that $-27 = -27$. This is always true, meaning there are infinitely many solutions to this system.</li>
</ol>
</div>

<h2 id="working-with-more-variables">Working with More Variables</h2>
<p>All of these methods we went over apply to systems with more variables as well. Just make sure that the number of equations matches (or exceeds) the number of variables you are using. Otherwise, won't have just $1$ solution (usually). We urge you to try to make some problems of your own using $3$ or more variables and $3$ or more different equations, and solve them on your own.</p>
<p>An equation cannot be used to express a statement of greater than or less than. For example, we can express that $8-2$ is equal to $6$ with an equation, but we can't say that $8-2$ is greater than $4$. How can we do that? We denote $>$ as greater than, and $<$ as less than (we can add a bar underneath to denote “or equal to”). Practically speaking, this is most useful when working with variables. For example, we might observe the sentence “5 less than twice a number is at most 25”. In this case, we would take the number to be a variable. The left hand side converts to $2x-5$ and the right side $25$. Then, at most means less than or equal to. So $2x-5 \le 25$. To solve this, we isolate the variable just like in an equation. In this instance, $2x \le 30$, or $x \le 15$. Instead of getting a finite amount of solutions, we instead get a range of possible values.</p>
<p>There are two properties to remember as well. First, when comparing inequalities, if $a \le b$, and $b \le c$, $a$ is also less than or equal to $c$. However, if $a < b$, and $c < b$, that says nothing about $a$ and $b$. Secondly, if we consider negative numbers, $-6$ is less than $-5$. But if we multiply $-6$ and $-5$ by $-1$, we would see that $6$ is greater than $5$. So, when we multiply across the inequality with a negative value, we must flip the inequality.</p>
<p>Consider the line created by a linear equation, for example, $y=x$. Graphically speaking, what would be greater than $y=x$? For this, we would look at the region where for every value of $x$, the values of $y$ in this region are always greater than the line. This is really just a fancy way of saying – to be greater than a line is to be above it. Similarly, to be less than a linear equation is to be below it. Finally, if we look to a system of inequalities, we will encounter more than one region. Then, the solution graphically becomes the intersection of those two regions.</p>

<h2 id="am-gm">AM-GM</h2>
<p>Take a semicircle, and construct an inscribed triangle along the diameter. Then the diameter of this semicircle is $a+b$ (as below). The radius is then $(a+b)/2$. Then, by similar triangles, we can find the height of the triangle to the diameter is the geometric mean of $a$ and $b$. Clearly, this height is less than the radius, no matter where the triangle is inscribed (unless it is the same as the radius, in which case $a=b$). Thus, we derive:</p>
<p>$(a+b)/2 \ge \sqrt{ab}$ where equality comes if $a=b$.</p>
<p>In fact, this inequality holds for further variables, such as including 3 variables or infinitely many.</p>

<h3 id="am-gm-hm-qm">AM-GM-HM-QM</h3>
<p>We know what a linear equation is, and similarly what exponents (like squaring does). We might be then provoked to wonder what happens when an equation has a higher degree. This is a polynomial, and especially when the highest degree is of power two, a quadratic equation. Quadratic equations most commonly fit the form $y=ax^2+bx+c$ (which may be seen as standard form), but can also be expressed in vertex form, $y=(x-h)^2+k$. Some key characteristics of quadratic equations is that they have a vertex as well as up to 2 zeros (or roots). Furthermore, they are symmetrical about the vertical line passing through the vertex. They often appear as a U shape.</p>
<p>Completing the square refers to a situation in which you have $x^2+2ax$. This appears to be a perfect square that has had a constant subtracted from it. In particular, $(x+a)^2=x^2+2ax+a^2$. So we can see that $x^2+2ax=(x+a)^2-a^2$. This can be applied even in situations such as in the standard form, of $ax^2+bx+c$ (for a variety of values). In this instance, the key is to factor $a$ before completing the square. Then, divide $b$ by 2 to get the value of $a$. For example, take $x^2+3x$. To complete the square here, we take half the value of $b$, which is $3$. Then $x^2+3x=(x+3/2)^2-(3/2)^2$, or $(x+3/2)^2-9/4$.</p>
<p>In the formula $ax^2+bx+c=0$, we wish to derive a perfect square and some excess constant remainder. Then, we can take the square root of the remainder and find solutions for $x$. In particular, we can note that for $(x+a)^2$, it results in $x^2+2ax+a^2$. Thus, we will see that upon factoring $a$ from $ax^2+bx+c$, we get $a(x^2+b/ax+c/a)$. Then, this could be factored as $a(x+b/2a)^2+\text{some remainder}$. When we expand our square, we get $ax^2+bx+b^2/4a+\text{some remainder} = x^2+bx+c$. Thus, our remainder must be $c- b^2/4a$ (or $(4ac-b^2)/4a$). Then, we know that $ax^2+bx+c=a(x+b/2a)^2+(4ac-b^2)/4a=0$. When we move the constant over and divide by $a$, we get $(x+b/2a)^2=(b^2-4ac)/4a^2$. Finally, taking the square root and moving the $b$ gets us $x = -b \pm \sqrt{b^2-4ac}/2a$.</p>
<p>This shows us that we can get the solutions to any quadratic equation using this formula. Furthermore, it can tell us about the amount of solutions that exist. For example, we will call the term $(b^2-4ac)$ the discriminant of the equation. When this discriminant is positive, the solutions are 2 (since this value can be added or subtracted from $-b$). Then, if it is $0$ there is only one solution ($b/2a$). If it is negative, the square root cannot be taken and thus there is no solution.</p>
<h4>Sum and Product of Roots</h4>
<p>Factoring quadratics can also be computed through some useful tricks. In the most simple cases with quadratics with leading coefficient $1$, such as $x^2+7x+12$, any factoring will have $(x-a)(x-b)$ where $a$ and $b$ are the zeroes of the quadratic. Then, if we expanded this, we would get $x^2-(a+b)x+ab$. This should show us that $ab=12$, and $a+b=-7$. What this means is that the roots of the equation must multiply to the constant and add to the inverse of the second coefficient. See Vieta's formulas below for more information.</p>

<h2 id="graphing-applications">Graphing Applications</h2>
<p>In order to graph quadratic equations, we should be mindful of the key features. Primarily, we know that the vertex of a quadratic is at (h,k) when the equation is y=(x-h)^2+k. From there, the quadratic equation must be symmetric about x=h, and has to pass through the zeros. Once the vertex has been fixed, set x to be values such as h+1, h+2, and h+3, plotting the y values. Connecting the curve and then doing the same on the other side of the equation yields the parabola.</p>
<p>Practically speaking, the vertex gives the key applications of a parabola. The vertex is either the maximum or minimum value of the parabola, depending on whether there is a negative before (x-h)^2.</p>
<p>The difference of two squares, $x^2-y^2$ can be represented by (x-y)(x+y). If we expand the factored form, we get x^2-xy+xy-y^2 = x^2-y^2.</p>
<p>This can be applied to variables and numbers.</p>
<p>Similarly, the difference/sum of cubes can be factored thusly:</p>
<p>$x^3+y^3=(x+y)(x^2-xy+y^2)$</p>
<p>$x^3-y^3=(x-y)(x^2+xy+y^2)$</p>
<p>$x^5+y^5 = (x+y)(x^4-x^3y+x^2y^2-xy^3+y^4)$</p>
<h2 id="squares-binomial">Squares/Powers of Binomials</h2>
<p>We observe in particular the squares of $(a+b)$ and $(a-b)$. These squares are commonly shown as $a^2+2ab+b^2$ and $a^2-2ab+b^2$ (by expanding). If we further extend to cubed powers, we can obtain $a^3+b^3+3ab(a+b)$ and $a^3-b^3-3ab(a-b)$.</p>
<p>It may become tedious to expand higher power polynomials. Luckily, we have a shortcut. The reader may be familiar with Pascal's triangle, which gives the coefficients of the $n$th power of $(a+b)^n$. Similarly, the binomial theorem tells us that the coefficient of the term $x^{n-k}y^k$ is simply ${n \choose k}$. In total, the coefficients will be ${n \choose 0}, {n \choose 1}, {n \choose 2}, \dots, {n \choose n-2}, {n \choose n-1}, {n \choose n}$.</p>

<h3 id="sfft">Simon's Favorite Factoring Trick (SFFT)</h3>
<p>Simon's Favorite Factoring Trick (SFFT) is a factoring idea that was popularized on AoPS forums. The basis of the trick is to notice that $(x+1)(y+1) = xy+x+y+1$, which allows the factorization of expressions like $xy+x+y$ by adding constants.</p>
<p>When you take the square root of something, you get the number that, when squared, produces your original value. Now, we know that the square of a real number is always positive, whether the original value is negative, zero, or positive. So, what do we do when we take the square root of a negative number then? The output obviously can't be a real number, so we create something known as imaginary numbers. When working with imaginary numbers, we define $\sqrt{-1}$ to be $i$. Thus, $\sqrt{-4} = 2i$, $\sqrt{-12} = 2\sqrt{3}i$, and so on. When dealing with fractions, we usually don't want imaginary numbers in our denominator. For example, to simplify $\frac{2}{i}$, we multiply top and bottom by $i$ to get $\frac{2i}{-1}$, aka $-2i$.</p>

<h2 id="complex-numbers">Complex Numbers</h2>
<p>Complex numbers are combinations of real numbers and imaginary numbers. For example, $3+4i$ is a complex number. When simplifying complex numbers in the denominator, you multiply top and bottom by something known as the conjugate. The conjugate of a complex number is the complex number with the sign of the imaginary part reversed. For example, the conjugate of $3+4i$ is $3-4i$. If we want to simplify $\frac{1}{2+\sqrt{3}i}$, simply multiply top and bottom by $2-\sqrt{3}i$. This will give you $2-\sqrt{3}i$ on top and $1$ on bottom, so your final answer is $2-\sqrt{3}i$.</p>



