<h2 id="functions-and-inverses">Functions and Inverses</h2>
<p>A function is a relationship between inputs and outputs. For every input, there is exactly one output.</p>
<p> Sometimes, we want to be able to undo the effects of a function. For example, if we have a function $f^{-1}$ such that $f^{-1}(f(x)) = x$, then we would be able to return the input to its original value. This $f^{-1}$ is called the inverse function of $f$. As rules, functions $f$ and $g$ are inverses if and only if:</p>
<p>$f(g(x)) = x$ for all $x$ in the domain of $g$</p>
<p>$g(f(x)) = x$ for all $x$ in the domain of $f$</p>
<p>Basically, if $f$ inverts $g$ then $g$ inverts $f$. So, how do we actually find these inverses? Well, when we graph a function, we're basically graphing $y = f(x)$. So, if we have $f(x) = 2x + 5$, we're going to be graphing $y = 2x + 5$. To find the inverse of this function, you swap the $x$ and $y$, and try to isolate $y$ once again. For example, we start with $y = 2x+5$, and swap the variables so that it becomes $x = 2y + 5$. Then, we isolate $y$ to get $y = \frac{x-5}{2}$. This is our inverse function. To confirm, let's plug in $2x+5$ into $\frac{x-5}{2}$. When we do so, we see that $\frac{2x+5-5}{2} = x$, so we know that our process has worked.</p>
<p>The reasoning behind this process is that we want to go from our $y$ output back to our original $x$ input, so we swap the relationships of our $x$ and $y$. When you look at a graph, you'll be able to tell when a function is invertible if it passes the horizontal line test. Basically, if you are able to draw a horizontal line through the graph such that it intersects $2$ or more points, the function is not invertible. This is because since there are multiple inputs that generate the same output, the inverse would theoretically have multiple outputs for the same input. Thus, there cannot exist an inverse function for such a graph.</p>


<div class="exercise-section">
