<p>We've gone over graphing functions a bit already, so now we want to focus on how graphs change when certain things</p>
<p>Radicals are fractional exponents. For example, $9^{\frac{3}{4}} = \sqrt[\leftroot{-2}\uproot{2}4]{9^3}$. The formula for a radical function is usually defined as $f(x) = \sqrt[\leftroot{-2}\uproot{2}n]{g(x)}$, where ${f(x)}^n = g(x)$. The most common example of the radical is the square root, or $f(x) = \sqrt[\leftroot{-2}\uproot{2}2]{g(x)}$. Therefore, if $g(x) = 9$, $f(x) = 3$ because $3^2 = 9$. The same logic can be appped to larger roots, with the cube root of 27 being 3, and the fourth root of 81 also being 3.</p>
<h2 id="properties-of-radicals">Properties of Radicals</h2>
<p>In the case of an even root, the number under the radical must be nonnegative to return a real result. For example, $\sqrt[\leftroot{-2}\uproot{2}2]{-2}$ is a non-real number, whereas $\sqrt[\leftroot{-2}\uproot{2}2]{2}$ is a real number.</p>
<h3>Odd Roots (first roots, cube roots):</h3>
<p>The expression under the radical can be any real number. For example, $\sqrt[\leftroot{-2}\uproot{2}3]{-8} = -2$, while $\sqrt[\leftroot{-2}\uproot{2}3]{8} = 2$.</p>
<h3>Multiplication:</h3>
<p>Square roots cannot be added, for example, $\sqrt{2} + \sqrt{2}$ is not equal to $\sqrt{4}$. However, $\sqrt{2} * \sqrt{2} = \sqrt{4}$. This allows us to simplify radical expressions. For example, $\sqrt{50} = \sqrt{25} * \sqrt{2}$. Then, $\sqrt{25} = 5$, which means $\sqrt{50} = 5\sqrt{2}$!</p>
<h3>Solving Procedure:</h3>
<p>The first step to solving a radical equation is eliminating the radical. This can be completed by raising both sides of the equation to the power of $n$, essentially going from $\sqrt{A} = B$ to $A = B^2$.</p>

