<h2 id="piecewise-absolute-value">Piecewise and Absolute Value Functions</h2>
<p>A piecewise function is usually depicted as:</p>
<p>\( f(x) = \begin{cases} -x & \text{if } x \le 0 \\ x & \text{if } x \ge 0 \end{cases} \)</p>
<p>Given this, we can think of a piecewise function as a function made from the pieces of other functions. For example, the absolute value function is a piecewise function. When $x>0$, the absolute value of $x = x$, but when $x<0$, the absolute value of $x = -x$.</p>
<p>Evaluating piecewise functions involves 2 steps:</p>
<p>- Identify the interval or condition met by the current x-coordinate.</p>
<p>- Evaluate the corresponding function.</p>
<p>It's important to treat each individual "piece" as a separate function over a separate domain- not all piecewise functions will be continuous, so it's important to consider each individual "piece" as an individual function.</p>
<p>The Absolute value of a number is defined as the distance it is away from 0, regardless of direction. For example, $|-4| = 4 = |4|$. It has many uses in mathematics, such as in distance, inequapties, and solving equations.</p>
<p>Three important identities of the Absolute Value function occur when we represent the absolute value as a piecewise function:</p>
<p>$f(x) = \begin{cases} -x & \text{if } x \le 0 \\ x & \text{if } x \ge 0 \end{cases}$</p>
<p>Rules:</p>
<p>1. The absolute value can never be negative, $|f(x)|>0$ for all $f(x)$.</p>
<p>2. $|x| = x$ for $x \ge 0$</p>
<p>3. $|x| = -x$ for $x \le 0$</p>
<p>Now that we know some basic principles of absolute value, let's consider its usage in distance and apply some transformations. In terms of distance, we have that $|a-b|=c$ means that $a$ and $b$ are $c$ units apart on the number line, regardless of units. This offers a simple way to solve for absolute value, because we can express this as $b = a \pm c$.</p>

