<h2 id="sequences-series">Sequences & Series</h2>

<h4 id="arithmetic-sequences-series">Arithmetic Sequences/Series</h4>

<p>An Arithmetic Sequence consists of terms in a progression in which they all have a common difference. For example, 1, 2, 3, 4, is an arithmetic sequence with a common difference $1$ and the starting term $1$. An arithmetic sequence has two important terms: the initial term and the common difference.</p>

<p>With this, we can create two formulas for the arithmetic sequence: one based on position, difference, and initial term (explicit formula), and one that uses the previous term to create a new term (recursive formula).</p>

<p>Our recursive formula can be written as current term = previous term + common difference, or $a_{n} = a_{n-1} + d$, with $d$ as the common difference and $a_{n}$ being the $n$th term of the sequence. Similarly, our explicit formula can be written as $a_{n} = a_{1} + d(n-1)$. The recursive formula serves more as the definition of an arithmetic progression, and the explicit formula allows us to find the $n$th term of a sequence.</p>

<h5 id="arithmetic-sums">Arithmetic Sums</h5>

<p>With this information, is it possible to find the sums of arithmetic sequences? The arithmetic sum formula goes $S_{n} = \frac{n}{2} * (a_{1} + a_{n})$. However, this can be expressed differently, such as $S_{n} = \frac{n}{2} * (2a + (n-1)d)$.</p>

