<h4 id="geometric-sequences-series">Geometric Sequences/Series</h4>

<p>A geometric sequence consists of a progression in which each term has a common ratio with the previous term. In essence, it is an arithmetic progression with multiplication rather than addition. Similar to an arithmetic progression, the two important terms of the geometric sequence are the initial term and the common ratio.</p>

<p>The recursive formula for the geometric series is defined as $a_{n} = a_{n-1} * r$, if $r$ is the common ratio. Then, the explicit formula is defined as $a_{n} = a_{0} * r^{n-1}$. This allows us to find the $n$th term of the progression with only the initial term and common difference.</p>

<h5 id="geometric-sums">Geometric Sums</h5>

<p>There are two types of geometric sums- those for infinite and finite series. In terms of an infinite series, the sum will converge to a number only when $|r| \le 1$, or $-1 \le r \le 1$. When these conditions are met, the formula for the infinite series is $S_{n} = \boxed{\frac{a}{1-r}}$.</p>

<p>In terms of the finite series, the formula is $S_{n} = a* (\frac{r^n-1}{r-1})$ for $r \neq 1$.</p>

