<h2 id="telescoping">Telescoping</h2>

<p>A telescoping series is a series in which most terms cancel out when the series is summed. Take the sum of all $\frac{1}{n}-\frac{1}{n+1}$ for all positive $n$. Given this sequence, its telescoping nature is easier to see when we write the first few terms of the series. We get $\frac{1}{1} - \frac{1}{2} + \frac{1}{2} - \frac{1}{3} + \frac{1}{3} … - \frac{1}{n}$. From this, we can see that all terms other than $1$ and $\frac{1}{n}$ cancel out, meaning the sum of the first $n$ terms of this sequence is $1-\frac{1}{n}$.</p>

<p>Telescoping sequences typically involve reasoning in order to find a pattern in between terms, but the pattern allows for simplification of incredibly complex sequences.</p>

